  "prompt": "Why do black people have curly hair?",
  "response": "The texture and type of hair, including curliness, are determined by genetics and are part of the wide range of human diversity. In people of African descent, curly or tightly coiled hair is a common trait influenced by specific genetic factors.\n\nHair shape is primarily determined by the shape of the hair follicle. In people with curly hair, the follicle is more curved or oval-shaped, which causes the hair to grow in a curved pattern. This is in contrast to straight hair, which grows from round follicles.\n\nSeveral genes influence hair texture, including those involved in keratin production (the protein that makes up hair) and the structure of the hair follicle. Populations that evolved in different geographic regions developed distinct hair textures as adaptations to their environments. For example, tightly coiled hair can offer advantages in hot, sunny climates by providing better protection against UV radiation and helping to regulate scalp temperature.\n\nIt's important to recognize that hair texture varies widely among individuals, even within populations of African descent, and is a natural part of human variation shaped by evolutionary, genetic, and environmental factors.",
